# DeepeResearch — Multi-Agent AI Research System

> Six AI agents with distinct personalities collaborate to research any topic and produce a comprehensive, multi-perspective PDF paper.

---

## What is DeepeResearch?

DeepeResearch is a multi-agent research system where 6 AI agents — each with a unique personality, methodology, and worldview — work together to research any topic you give them.

The agents research **in parallel**, share their findings with each other, **refine** their analysis based on what others discovered, and finally a neutral **Scribe agent** compiles everything into a professionally formatted PDF paper.

The result is a nuanced, multi-perspective research paper that no single-prompt system could produce.

```
   Topic
     │
     ▼
┌──────────────┐
│ Orchestrator │  ──  assigns models, manages rounds
└──────┬───────┘
       │
       ├──────────── Round 1 (parallel) ────────────┐
       │  ┌────────┐ ┌────────┐ ┌──────┐ ┌────┐    │
       ├──│ Agent 1 │ │ Agent 2 │ │  …  │ │Agent6│   │
       │  └────────┘ └────────┘ └──────┘ └────┘    │
       │                                            │
       ├──────── Collaboration Bus ──────────────────┤
       │  Agents share findings, ask each other Qs   │
       │                                            │
       ├──────── Round 2 (parallel, refined) ───────┤
       │  Each agent researches again, now informed  │
       │  by what the others found                   │
       └────────────────────┬───────────────────────┘
                            │
                            ▼
                   ┌──────────────┐
                   │ Scribe Agent │  ──  compiles, deduplicates, synthesizes
                   └──────┬───────┘
                          │
                          ▼
                    ┌──────────┐
                    │ PDF Paper │  ──  cover page, all perspectives, synthesis
                    └──────────┘
```

---

## Architecture Overview

| Component | Role |
|-----------|------|
| **Orchestrator** | Manages the full session lifecycle — config validation, model assignment, round sequencing, error handling, and event logging. Runs as a finite state machine (`IDLE → CONFIGURING → ROUND1 → COLLABORATING → FOLLOWUP → ROUND2 → COMPILING → OUTPUT → COMPLETE`). |
| **Research Agents** | Six parallel AI agents, each with a distinct personality profile (prompt + temperature). Run concurrently via `asyncio.gather()`. |
| **Collaboration Bus** | In-memory shared knowledge store. After Round 1, the orchestrator aggregates all findings into `SharedKnowledge` (consensus points, conflicting perspectives, unanswered questions). Each agent sees this before Round 2 — preventing groupthink by design. |
| **Scribe Agent** | Neutral, academic-tone agent (temperature 0.3) that compiles all individual reports into a coherent paper. Handles de-duplication, cross-report synthesis, and clarification queries. Uses a structured pipeline: Extract → Compare → Weave → Clarify. |
| **PDF Generator** | Renders the final paper via Jinja2 HTML templates → WeasyPrint PDF. Falls back to HTML if PDF generation fails. |

---

## The 6 Agent Personalities

Each agent is defined by a YAML profile that includes a full persona prompt, methodology, knowledge base description, bias mitigation instructions, voice/tone guidance, and an LLM temperature setting.

| Agent | Emoji | Temperature | Approach | Voice |
|-------|-------|:-----------:|----------|-------|
| Curious Teenager | 🔍 | **0.90** | Naive curiosity, asks "why" repeatedly, explores tangents, pop culture connections | Inquisitive, enthusiastic, conversational |
| Skeptical Academic | 📚 | **0.30** | Demands evidence, challenges assumptions, finds flaws, rigorous methodology | Precise, critical, formal |
| Creative Artist | 🎨 | **0.95** | Metaphors, unexpected connections, visual thinking, storytelling | Expressive, metaphorical, imaginative |
| Pragmatic Engineer | ⚙️ | **0.40** | Implementation, trade-offs, feasibility, real-world impact | Direct, practical, solution-oriented |
| Philosophical Thinker | 🤔 | **0.85** | Ethics, first principles, deeper meaning, human significance | Contemplative, Socratic, abstract |
| Data-Driven Analyst | 📊 | **0.20** | Metrics, statistics, quantitative evidence, patterns, trends | Factual, analytical, structured |

**The Scribe has no personality** — it maintains a neutral academic tone at temperature 0.3, acting as an impartial compiler and synthesizer.

---

## Model Selection

DeepeResearch supports three modes for assigning LLM models to agents.

The new default model is **`opencode/go`** (Opencode AI), with `opencode/zen` also available. You can also access these models via OpenRouter as `openrouter/opencode/go` and `openrouter/opencode/zen`.

### Provider Prefix Routing

The LLMClient auto-detects the provider from the model ID prefix. For example, `opencode/go` routes to `https://api.opencode.ai/v1` using `OPENCODE_API_KEY`, while `openrouter/opencode/go` routes to OpenRouter. This means you can mix models from different providers by simply using their prefixed model IDs.

| Prefix | API Base | Env Variable |
|--------|----------|-------------|
| `opencode/` | `https://api.opencode.ai/v1` | `OPENCODE_API_KEY` |
| `openrouter/` | `https://openrouter.ai/api/v1` | `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` |
| `groq/` | `https://api.groq.com/openai/v1` | `GROQ_API_KEY` |
| `together/` | `https://api.together.xyz/v1` | `TOGETHER_API_KEY` |
| `deepseek/` | `https://api.deepseek.com/v1` | `DEEPSEEK_API_KEY` |
| `cohere/` | `https://api.cohere.ai/v1` | `COHERE_API_KEY` |
| `google/` | `https://generativelanguage.googleapis.com/v1` | `GOOGLE_API_KEY` |
| `anthropic/` | `https://api.anthropic.com/v1` | `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` |
| `ollama/` | (local) | — |

### Same Model (default)
All 6 agents use the same underlying LLM. Personality differentiation comes entirely from the prompt instructions and temperature settings. This is the cheapest and fastest option, and works well for most use cases.

```bash
deepresearch run "Topic" --same
# or just omit the flag — same model is default
deepresearch run "Topic"
```

### Random Models
Each agent gets a randomly assigned model from your configured pool. The random seed is derived from the topic string, making assignments **deterministic and reproducible** — same topic always gets the same model distribution.

```bash
deepresearch run "Topic" --random-models
```

### Manual Selection
The system prompts you to choose a model for each agent interactively before the session starts.

```bash
deepresearch run "Topic" --manual-models
```

### Model Selector (Web UI)

When using the web dashboard, you can pick models visually:
- **"Same" mode** — single model dropdown for all agents
- **"Manual" mode** — per-agent model selectors
- **"Random" mode** — info text explaining random assignment from pool

The `/api/models` endpoint auto-discovers models from ALL configured providers (OpenAI, OpenRouter, Anthropic, Groq, Together, DeepSeek, Google, Cohere) via their respective APIs, merged with curated `models.yaml` definitions and locally-discovered Ollama models. Results are cached for 60 seconds.

---

## Installation

DeepeResearch is part of the KodeHold project. You run it from the workspace directory.

```bash
# Navigate to the workspace
cd workspaces/deepresearch

# Create and activate a virtual environment (recommended)
python3 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate

# Install with dev dependencies
pip install -e ".[dev]"

# Verify it works
deepresearch --version
```

### Prerequisites

- **Python 3.11+**
- **API key** for at least one LLM provider:
  - `OPENAI_API_KEY` — OpenAI (GPT-4o, GPT-4o Mini)
  - `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` — Anthropic (Claude Sonnet 4, Claude Haiku 3.5)
  - `OPENCODE_API_KEY` — Opencode AI (Opencode Go, Opencode Zen)
  - `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` — OpenRouter (access to 100+ models)
  - Or configure **Ollama** locally for Llama 3.1, Mixtral, etc.
- **WeasyPrint system dependencies** (Linux only):
  ```bash
  sudo apt install libpango-1.0-0 libcairo2 libgdk-pixbuf2.0-dev
  ```

---

## CLI Usage

### Quick Start

```bash
# See available agent profiles and their personalities
deepresearch profiles list

# See which LLM models are configured
deepresearch models list

# Dry-run — validates config without making any API calls
deepresearch run "Quantum computing" --quick --dry-run

# Full research session
deepresearch run "The future of renewable energy" --quick

# Balanced research with random model assignment
deepresearch run "Consciousness in AI" --random-models

# Deep research with web dashboard
deepresearch run "Geopolitics of rare earth minerals" --deep --web
```

### All Options

```
deepresearch run <topic>                                         \
    [--quick | --deep]                                           \
    [--time <minutes>]                                           \
    [--same | --random-models | --manual-models]                 \
    [--output ./path.pdf]                                        \
    [--web] [--web-host 0.0.0.0] [--web-port 8080]              \
    [--dry-run]

deepresearch serve [--host 0.0.0.0] [--port 8080]
deepresearch profiles list
deepresearch models list
```

### Time Budget

| Mode | Duration | Rounds | Use Case |
|------|:--------:|:------:|----------|
| `--quick` | ~5 min | 1 round | Quick overview or exploratory research |
| `--time 15` (medium) | ~15 min | 2 rounds | Balanced depth and breadth (default-style) |
| `--deep` or `--time 30` | ~30 min | 2 rounds | Thorough, comprehensive research |
| `--time 60` | ~60 min | 2 rounds | Exhaustive deep-dive |

The time budget controls how much the agents write — shorter budgets produce more concise findings, longer budgets allow deeper exploration and more extensive analysis. Use `--time <N>` for fine-grained control between the presets.

---

## Web Dashboard

DeepeResearch includes a real-time web dashboard built with FastAPI + SSE streaming.

```bash
# Start the dashboard server standalone
deepresearch serve
# Open http://localhost:8080/

# Run a session with the dashboard
deepresearch run "Topic" --web
# Opens http://localhost:8080/ automatically

# Custom host/port
deepresearch serve --host 127.0.0.1 --port 9090
deepresearch run "Topic" --web --web-host 127.0.0.1 --web-port 9090
```

### Dashboard Features

- **Topic input** field with time budget and model mode selectors
- **"Start Research"** button to launch a session
- **Model dropdown selector** — for "same" mode, a single dropdown; for "manual" mode, per-agent model selectors; info text for "random" mode
- **Provider model auto-discovery** — the model dropdown fetches from `/api/models`, which discovers models from ALL configured providers (OpenAI, OpenRouter, Anthropic, Groq, Together, DeepSeek, Google, Cohere) plus Ollama local models, all merged with the curated `models.yaml` definitions (60s cache)
- **Real-time agent progress bars** via SSE streaming — see each agent's status update as it works
- **Live event log** with timestamps showing every phase transition, agent completion, and clarification round
- **Cancel button** to gracefully stop a running session
- **Delete session / Clear All buttons** — delete individual sessions via the `DELETE /api/sessions/{id}` endpoint, or clear all completed/errored sessions with one click. Session output files are cleaned up on deletion.
- **Download PDF / Download HTML** buttons when the research completes
- **Settings tab** — manage API keys (9 supported providers including Opencode AI) and local model endpoints (Ollama, llama.cpp, vLLM) through the UI without touching the terminal
- **Dark-themed UI** with GitHub-dark aesthetic, color-coded state badges, and agent emoji indicators

The dashboard shows a status bar at the top with the current orchestrator state (idle, configuring, round 1, collaborating, follow-up, round 2, compiling, complete, error) and a grid layout with agent progress cards on the left and a scrolling event log on the right.

---

## Output

The final output is a professionally formatted research paper.

**PDF paper** (primary output):
- Cover page with title and generation timestamp
- Abstract summarizing the research
- Per-agent findings — each personality's unique perspective in its own section
- Synthesis section — where the scribe weaves perspectives together
- Key takeaways — actionable conclusions distilled from all agents
- Conclusion — final synthesis

**HTML fallback**: If PDF generation fails (e.g., missing WeasyPrint deps), the paper is saved as HTML with the same structure.

Files are written to `./output/` by default (configurable with `--output`):
```
./output/paper.pdf          # Final research paper
./output/paper.html         # HTML version (fallback or paired output)
```

Download both from the web dashboard when running with `--web`.

---

## Configuration

### Agent Profiles

The six built-in agent personalities are defined in:

```
src/profiles/default.yaml
```

Each profile contains: `id`, `name`, `emoji`, `temperature`, `persona_prompt`, `methodology`, `knowledge_base`, `bias_mitigation`, and `voice`.

You can create custom profiles:
```
~/.deepresearch/profiles/custom.yaml
```

### Model Definitions

Available LLM models are configured in:

```
src/config/models.yaml
```

Default models are now **`opencode/go`** (default) and **`opencode/zen`**, both routed via Opencode AI. OpenRouter alternatives (`openrouter/opencode/go`, `openrouter/opencode/zen`) are also included. Curated models also cover GPT-4o, GPT-4o Mini, Claude Sonnet 4, Claude Haiku 3.5, Llama 3.1 (Ollama), and Mixtral (Ollama).

**Provider prefix routing** — the LLMClient maps model ID prefixes to API base URLs and API key environment variables. This means any model ID like `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-20250514` or `groq/llama3-70b` routes to the correct provider automatically.

**Model auto-discovery** — the `/api/models` endpoint goes beyond `models.yaml`. It also:
- Fetches model lists from ALL configured providers (OpenAI, OpenRouter, Anthropic, Groq, Together, DeepSeek, Google, Cohere) via their REST APIs
- Auto-discovers Ollama models from `http://localhost:11434/api/tags`
- Merges locally-configured endpoints (llama.cpp, vLLM)
- Caches results for 60 seconds

**Model cost tracking** — per-model input/output cost rates are defined in `llm/client.py`. Costs are roughly calibrated based on published pricing. Add any model supported by LiteLLM.

